<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-357-488  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 357 488.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Transactions on Computers  June 1989 v38 n6 p881(11).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Spare capacity as a means of fault detection and diagnosis inmultiprocessor systems.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Dahbura, Anton T.; Sabnani, Krishan K.; Hery, William J.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Two strategies, one preemptive, that use the spare capacity in amultiprocessor computer system for detecting and diagnosingprocessor-level faults in such a system are developed.andP;  Eachstrategy involves assignment of a process to two processors, onethe normal or primary unit for the process and a secondaryprocessor that would otherwise be idle.andP;  Discrepancies in resultsbetween the two processors indicates that one is faulty(localization is not considered in this paper).andP;  Almost nodegradation in system response time is experience in moderatelyloaded multiprocessors when spare capacity is used for faultdetection.andP;  Atandamp;T Bell Laboratories is implementing ahigh-performance signal-processing multiprocessor system, the BellData Flow Architecture multiprocessor, that incorporates sparecapacity for fault detection into the design.andP;  Details of thefault-detection strategies are described.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Capacity ManagementSystem DesignFailure AnalysisMultiprocessingFault Tolerance.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   The system S consisting of m processors and queue Q. (chart)The state-transition-rate diagram for an M-M-m queuing system.andO;(chart)The state-transition-rate diagram for the preemptive strategy.andO;(chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>